{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"67ebd20f-a3b5-4957-bcdc-ebc054cbaab9","content":"Neither — use **`dotnet watch`**.\n\n- **`dotnet watch`** monitors your source files and automatically rebuilds/reruns when changes are detected. This is the hot reload mechanism in .NET.\n- **`dotnet run`** executes once and exits — no file watching.\n- **`dotnet test`** runs tests once and exits — no file watching either.\n\nFor your test project, you'd use:\n\n```bash\ndotnet watch test\n```\n\nThis will re-run your tests automatically whenever you save a file change. For an app project, you'd use `dotnet watch run`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4ed98053-41a1-4765-9d06-0d869fe686ed","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET hot reload functionality - specifically whether to use `dotnet test` or `dotnet run` to benefit from hot reload. Let me look at what's in the working directory to understand the context.","outputTokens":200,"requestId":"67CE:192B19:188F287:1B97308:69FD41AD"},"id":"7bd6f7b0-f241-4156-88af-352ad9f223a3","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:51:47.913Z","parentId":"cca92ec8-c5e1-4a07-9b25-9e76af7c522c"}
